I'm building the latest commit 85b0d4dfc0 locally with Maven 3.0.5. The build succeeds with JDK 1.8 (u40), but fails with JDK 1.7 (u71):

```
Failed tests:   TestTrailingCommas(net.razorvine.serpent.test.ParserTest): expected:<{'[a':1,'b':2,'c':3]}> but was:<{'[b':2,'c':3,'a':1]}>
```

It looks like the iteration order of Java Collection classes has changed between JDK 1.7 and 1.8. We can solve this problem by switching from `java.util.HashMap` to `java.util.LinkedHashMap`:
```
diff --git a/java/src/main/java/net/razorvine/serpent/Parser.java b/java/src/main/java/net/razorvine/serpent/Parser.java
index 3033c2f..2ea0c23 100644
--- a/java/src/main/java/net/razorvine/serpent/Parser.java
+++ b/java/src/main/java/net/razorvine/serpent/Parser.java
@@ -10,8 +10,8 @@ package net.razorvine.serpent;
 import java.io.UnsupportedEncodingException;
 import java.math.BigInteger;
 import java.util.ArrayList;
-import java.util.HashMap;
 import java.util.HashSet;
+import java.util.LinkedHashMap;
 import java.util.List;
 import java.util.Map;
 import java.util.Set;
@@ -314,7 +314,7 @@ public class Parser
 			throw new ParseException("expected '}'");
 		
 		// make sure it has dict semantics (remove duplicate keys)
-		Map<INode, INode> fixedDict = new HashMap<INode, INode>(elts.size());
+		Map<INode, INode> fixedDict = new LinkedHashMap<INode, INode>(elts.size());
 		for(INode e: elts)
 		{
 			KeyValueNode kv = (KeyValueNode)e;
```

Given a yang model
```
module test {
   namespace "http://error.com";
   prefix "error";

   leaf hex_default {
       type int32;
       default 0x8100;
   }
   leaf octal_default { 
       type int32;
       default 071;
   }
}
```
When I run pyang on it, I see the following: 

test.yang:7: error: the value "0x8100" does not match its base type - not an integer
test.yang:11: error: the value "071" does not match its base type - not an integer

In RFC 6020, section 9.2.1 (https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6020#section-9.2.1)
```
For convenience, when specifying a default value for an integer in a
   YANG module, an alternative lexical representation can be used, which
   represents the value in a hexadecimal or octal notation.  The
   hexadecimal notation consists of an optional sign ("+" or "-"), the
   characters "0x" followed a number of hexadecimal digits, where
   letters may be uppercase or lowercase.  The octal notation consists
   of an optional sign ("+" or "-"), the character "0" followed a number
   of octal digits.
```

